Profile:




































Welcome!

To learn more about Rolfing® Structural Integration, click this link: https://www.daviddelaney-rolfing.com/
 

Although I am passionate about and love working with everyone and have done so since 1985 when I was certified as a Rolfer, I also specialize in working with singers as well as other performing artists, who use their voice in their work. I have worked with professional singers and actors from the Broadway stage, the opera, pop & rock worlds, etc., most of that time in NYC. My work comes out of my own personal experience as an actor/ singer whose voice was dramatically freed and uncovered by the Rolfing® process in 1979-80. I am trained in the physiological side of the Bel Canto school of singing voice and studied, apprenticed & collaborated with the Broadway singing voice teacher Margaret Laughlin Riddleberger from 1979 to 2002, who sang at the Metropolitan Opera herself.  

Our body is our instrument. Singing demands full intrinsic body unification and elasticity. I have spent 38 years working with singers, helping them accelerate their development in achieving and maintaining vocal mastery; minimum use of breath, minimum tension in the throat and producing maximum power and resonance.
 
 











This drawing above is by the famous artist Bernhard Siegfried Albinus (1697-1770). It shows the intrinsic layer of musculature, called the emotional muscles, also called survival muscles; what I now call the singer's muscles.


The term intrinsic here specifically relates to the emotional musculature, also called core muscles today; what I call the singer's muscles.  Skilled Rolfing® is unsurpassed in its ability to bring the singer's body toward a significantly improved vertical posture, where a threshold of freedom in this intrinsic muscle layer is achieved as a naturally outcome. Adaptability and elasticity in this intrinsic muscle layer is primary for both the ability to listen well (a key skill for the virtuoso singer), as well as for innovative singing where you will never have a vocal problem, no matter how much you sing.
 
Rolfing helps a singer discover and achieve what is known as the listening posture, also called the singer's posture; really one and the same. Without this postural verticality that is initiated from a relaxed and adaptable core, a singer has no choice but to sing with a degree of force, tension and constraint. And the hallmark of authentic singing is body flexibility, elasticity and relaxation.

We all carry tension/fear in our bodies that are the result of unresolved experiences from our infancy and childhood, that manifest as body tension. This held tension accumulates year after year, often the degree to which it  is unbeknownst to us.  It eventually effects our body structure and posture by an overall body shortening that will eventually manifest as a twisting in the joints, affecting our mobility and overall resilience.
 
When a singer is under the intense pressure of having to sing in public with all the attendant fear and anxiety day after day, this accumulated unresolved fear/tension will show up in the form of limited vocal emission and constrained vocal resonance. Discovering and developing the somatic sensory-motor skills that are the same for speaking and singing are key to vocal longevity.  And this level of skill cannot even be discovered without a minimum of body freedom and good listening posture, what I call the "Singer's Posture" in my upcoming book, "Intrinsic SingingSM".
 
 

David Delaney, Advanced Certified Rolfer®   
Masters Degree in Counseling Psychology
Licensed Professional Counselor (Colorado)

As a Certified Advanced Rolfer  with over 20 years experience, I combine structural understanding and anatomical knowledge with an open-minded intuitive approach to help transform the human body.  Since the beginning of my career I have dedicated a great deal of time to advancing my skills with additional training in Visceral Manipulation and Biomechanics.  Visceral Manipulation is based on the principle that all organs have an inherent motion and necessary range of motion; any res

Profile:

As a Certified Advanced Rolfer  with over 20 years experience, I combine structural understanding and anatomical knowledge with an open-minded intuitive approach to help transform the human body.  Since the beginning of my career I have dedicated a great deal of time to advancing my skills with additional training in Visceral Manipulation and Biomechanics.  Visceral Manipulation is based on the principle that all organs have an inherent motion and necessary range of motion; any restriction to an organ results in a misalignment in the skeletal-muscular body. The physiology of each organ is dependent on its range of motion within the visceral cavity. Biomechanics allows one to identify and determine how to correct asymmetries in the body. As we experience large or small injuries in life, our body seeks to adapt by either exaggerating these irregularities or driving individual body parts out of pattern. As a Rolfer  I seek to engage these asymmetries in the body to determine there driving force.

In addition to my private practice, I have been an instructor in the Rolf Institute?s Phase I: Foundations of Rolfing Structural Integration in Boulder. As a Class room teacher I encourage students to build a strong framework of science theory and philosophy of Rolfing and to explore and master these concepts through personal exploration. As a mentor to students in the Rolf training process, I provide one-on-one teaching experience using a comfortable and highly attentive teaching style of learning, whether that's by allowing students to struggle through problems on their own, or by giving students as much or as little feedback on Rolfing techniques, as required.

I maintain a private practice with normal working days that include Thurday through Sunday. My sessions last about an hour and fifteen minutes and cost $160. per session. I accept cash, check and credit cards. For an Appointment call 720-276-1972 or click website to book an appointment today.

Profile:

Kevin McCarthy is a Somatic Experiencing® Practitioner, Advanced Rolfer and Rolf Movement® Practitioner specializing in the effects of trauma and chronic pain on the body. 

Originally trained in Boulder, Colorado at the Rolf Institute® for Structural Integration, with further training in trauma work through the Somatic Experiencing® Trauma Institute, Kevin's specialized practice brings a deep and studied knowledge of the body together with an appreciation for the impact of the mind and perception on our own ability to heal. 

He has additional training in osteopathic manipulation, cranial sacral therapy, visceral manipulation, energy work, trauma therapy, myofascial release, and holds an Advanced certification in Rolfing® Structural Integration and a specialized certification in Rolf Movement®. He is board-certified by the International Association of Structural Integrators®.

Kevin's 15 years of experience, along with these many and diverse skills are combined into powerful sessions dedicated to helping people find depth and meaning in their own healing experience. Kevin's sessions are a surprising and effective mix of talk therapy, manual intervention and movement exploration structured to support the client's realization of their emotional, mental and physical health in a safe and welcoming environment.

Profile:

Years of chronic low back pain brought me as a client to Rolfing? Structural Integration.? When I experienced results such as complete relief from my back pain, increased body awareness, and increased self esteem, I decided to pursue a career as a Certified Rolfer.  Rolfing has also helped me to recover from two motor vehicle accidents and has kept my body free and limber to support me in physical activity.? Rolfing SI has also been an incredible healing modality for my entire family.

I have had to fortune to study with a few first generation Rolfers who trained directly under Dr. Rolf such as Jan Sultan and Sharon Wheeler. Additionally, I have studied Craniosacral Therapy and Lymph Drainage Therapy, two osteopathic techniques which can be used to support the goals of Rolfing Structural Integration. ?More recently I have seen my practice transform as I have incorporated Neural Mobilization techniques to release tissue in deep and profound ways.

I believe that the crux of my work is a partnership with you and your body. ?In a way similiar to a midwife facilating a natural process like birth I see Rolfers as facilitating another natural process in the body: Integration or Self-Organization of the body. ?We do much more than just releasing tight or strained tissues; we help to get those tissues and parts of the body working together to bring greater balance to the whole. ?This experience varies from person to person, but it is common to hear reports of "lightness" and "easiness" in the body.?

I would be glad to talk with you in person about your goals and how Rolfing? Structural Integration may help.

I first found Rolfing Structural Integration after I had tried many different approaches to heal from daily work life and injuries sustained during my career in Wildland Fire. I spent 13 years as a Wildland Firefighter, working for 6 years on Helena Hotshots, a few years on a hand crew, Helitack crew and a Wildland Fire Module. I finally found relief from my knee and neck pain after my sessions with Rolfing. I knew that Wildland Firefighting was not sustainable for me anymore and I grew curious about Rolfing. I started school at the Dr. Ida Rolf Institute in Boulder, CO January 2020 and after persevering through school delays due to the pandemic and having another child, I graduated as a Certified Rolfer. I am so excited to be opening Mountain Roots Rolfing® Structural Integration in Cody, WY. I grew up in Mammoth Hot Springs inside Yellowstone National Park and have spent most of my life living around the Greater Yellowstone Ecosystem. I love the ebb and flow of the seasons and life in the GYE. I am so excited to bring Rolfing to Cody, Wyoming! Hope to see you soon!

Named after its founder, Dr. Ida P. Rolf, Rolfing Structural Integration is a form of bodywork that reorganizes the connective tissues, called fascia, that permeate the entire body.
More than fifty years ago, Dr. Rolf recognized that the body is inherently a system of seamless networks of tissues rather than a collection of separate parts.  

Essentially, the Rolfing SI process enables the body to regain the natural integrity of its form, thus enhancing postural efficiency and your freedom of movement. 

Please contact me directly for additional information about my practice.

After more than 23 years of study, practice and professional certification, I offer treatments that include techniques to relieve persistent pain and discomfort.

I bring my compassion, mind and spirit to be with you on your healing journey.

Chronic musculoskeletal pain
Headaches and Migraines
Sciatica

Repetitive strain injuries, e.g.carpal tunnel syndrome

Restricted range of motion

Rolfing Structural Integration is a method of deep manipulation of the connective tissues of the body, developed by Dr. Ida P. Rolf. Profile:
Rolfing Structural Integration is a method of deep manipulation of the connective tissues of the body, developed by Dr. Ida P. Rolf. Her intention was to create a system of postural restructuring and movement re-patterning, in order to promote ease and balance in the body with a corresponding effect on the mind. A Rolfer is highly trained to see, and address the complex ways in which a body-mind is relating to itself and its environment. The more balanced these relationships are, the more choice we will have in our experience. Through hands-on manipulation, and movement (perceptual) education, Rolfing is a very precise and effective way to change deep-set habits of posture, movement, and orientation.
Rolfing Structural Integration is a method of deep manipulation of the connective tissues of the body, developed by Dr. Ida P. Rolf. Her intention was to create a system of postural restructuring and movement re-patterning, in order to promote ease and balance in the body and therefore the mind. A Rolfer is highly trained to see, and address the complex ways in which a body-mind is relating to itself and its environment. The more balanced these relationships are, the more choice we will have in our experience. Through hands-on manipulation, and movement (perceptual) education, Rolfing is a very precise and effective way to change deep-set habits of posture, movement, and orientation.

Profile:

Being put into twister cable braces at the age of four to correct "pigeon-toed" walking was the spark that ignited the fire of my life-long interest in the structural organization of the human body. I have been in private practice as a Certified Rolfer™ since 1996, completing the Advanced Rolfing Training in 2000 and Rolf Movement Training in 2002.

In addition to Rolfing training I have studied pilates, craniosacral therapy, and somatic approaches to healing trauma. I have a deep and abiding interest in body-oriented psychotherapies. I also hold certification from the Certification Board for Structural Integration. My personal movement practices include many years of classical dance training, a strong yoga practice and my current passion, salsa dancing.

Please visit my website www.RedwoodEmpireRolfing.com for additional information about my practice, to schedule an appointment, or purchase online gift certificates.

Profile:

Clients choose how they want to work with me, either "fix-it" sessions (one or more) to address specific pain or posture issues, or the traditional Rolfing work (10-session basic series, 5-session advanced series, or tune-ups).

Besides Advanced certification in Rolfing Structural Integration, I have advanced training in visceral work and craniosacral work, and training in manual therapy for inflamed nerves (the source of many pain issues). I will incorporate these when it's desired and needed to relieve pain and improve alignment. I am also a teacher of the Diamond Approach®, a modern path of consciousness work, and am particularly enthusiastic to work with clients interested in mind-body-spirit connections.

I do not bill any insurances but can provide receipts for you to pursue reimbursement.

My office is in the Phinney Ridge neighborhood of Seattle, convenient to Ballard, Green Lake, Wallingford, and the University District. 

Please see my website for details, www.wholebodyintegration.com, or call for a free phone consultation.

My Approach: I came to Rolfing SI with a curiosity, 'could structural integration help me feel stronger, and more centered in my inner, emotional life?"  After several years of studying psychology and being involved in body-centered psychotherapy, I came up against personal growth walls that 'talking about' could not longer help to solve for me.  I bring a unique intuition and knowledge of body-centered psychology in the background of my practice, along with deep interest in how family his
Read More...
Profile:

My Approach:

I came to Rolfing SI with a curiosity, 'could structural integration help me feel stronger, and more centered in my inner, emotional life?"  After several years of studying psychology and being involved in body-centered psychotherapy, I came up against personal growth walls that 'talking about' could not longer help to solve for me.  I bring a unique intuition and knowledge of body-centered psychology in the background of my practice, along with deep interest in how family history informs present structure, and how a body organizies around belilef systems.  I work structurally with an eye on how our inner psychic life has a profound effect on how we organize and carry our bodies through the world. 

I have a background working with infants and small children which has informed my touch, but also reminds me that we've all come through the stress of dependency, including birth.  For me, it is a joy to explore how some of our earliest physical experiences continue to inform our current structure (in posture, movement, ways we hold ourselves, and even how tissue organizes.)

I see clients in both Indianapolis and Bloomington, IN.  Please contact me for information about my practice or to schedule a session.   You can learn more at allisondistler.com

Profile:

Amy Iadarola is a Certified Advanced Rolfer® and has been a professional bodyworker for over 20 years, 12 of which she worked at a physical therapy clinic that specialized in dance medicine. Over the years, her clients have ranged from performing artists and elite athletes to people living with chronic pain and other chronic conditions such as multiple sclerosis, Parkinson’s disease, joint hypermobility disorder, and myofascial pain syndrome.

In 2003, Amy was certified in Pilates, which remains influential in her Rolfing practice. Sessions typically incorporate 1 or 2 gentle, Pilates-based exercises to activate the client’s deep stabilizing muscles and support the changes achieved with the hands-on work.

Her practice is also informed by 25 years of experience in dance and movement and 15 years in public health.

Profile:

Holly is a Certified Rolfer™ and also practices Visceral Manipulation, Craniosacral Therapy, and Neural Mobilization. In her multi-systems approach to bodywork, Holly weaves between all the tissues of the body—fascia, organs, nerves, bones, brain, fluids, muscles, and glands. She also explores beyond physical structures to behavioral, lifestyle, emotional, energetic, and thought patterns, which can limit us from living more freely and fully. Holly empowers her clients to make long-lasting transformations by educating them; improving awareness of their bodies' messages, shifting their relationship with pain, and providing logistical support for lifestyle changes. Holly completed her Rolfing training in 2008, and she also holds undergraduate degrees with honors in American studies and sociology from KU. She runs Kinetikos Bodywork Therapy, and with her husband, Brett Stoppel, purchased the Vitality Health Collective building in 2016 to create a space for collaboration amongst holistic health care practitioners in Lawrence, KS. She and Brett live in Lawrence with their three children – EJ, Hazel, and Emerson. Holly is not currently seeking new clients and recommends her Structural Integration officemates, Cindi Thomas, Risa Kearn, and Samuel Beecher for bodywork.

Profile:

Keith was certified as a Rolfer® in 1997 by the Rolf Institute during the 700 hour basic course. He later completed 300 more hours of continuing education and Advanced coursework. He was certified as an Advanced Rolfer© in November 2001. Keith has been a Massage Therapist in private practice since 1993. He graduated from the Cayce/ Reilly school of Massotherapy, located in Virginia Beach, VA in April ’04. This extensive 600 hour program was based on the unique integration of physiotherapy and transpersonal studies. During the first semester studies focused on a specific Cayce/ Reilly protocol. In the second semester he had courses in advanced techniques, Sports massage, Swedish, Reflexology, and Hydrotherapy. Simultaneously he attended basic through advanced Jin Shin Do Acupressure workshops. Keith went on to attend workshops in Reiki, Neuromuscular Therapy, Cranio-Sacral Therapy, Applied Kinesiology (Touch for Health), Somato- Emotional Release , Visceral Manipulation,Tui Na, Shiatsu, & Source Point. Keith also is a nationally certified Acupuncturist. He graduated in 2006 from a 3000 hour, 4 year program.

Matthew Berean
Certified Advanced Rolfer

320 W. Washington
Ann Arbor, MI 48103

Website: MandalaAwareness.net
Matthew Berean integrates long experience with anatomical and cognitive techniques to benefit his clients. His experience in athletics extends over thirty years as a rower and a coach. Read More...
Profile:

Matthew Berean integrates long experience with anatomical and cognitive techniques to benefit his clients. His experience in athletics extends over thirty years as a rower and a coach. His study of cultural mental constructs began as a boy with an intense interest in the myths of multiple cultures. He learned meditation as a teenager. He draws on his personal experience and his training in assisting clients.
 
His formal training began with Rolfing Structural Integration, and expanded into extensive Osteopathy based manipulation, particularly Visceral, Neural, Vascular, and Cranial manipulation. He subsequently added further training and certifications in Buteyko Breathing Method and Orofacial Myofunctional Therapy to more effectively address structural and functional issues related to breathing, airway, and sleep. 
 
The experience from these trainings integrates seamlessly into his teaching experience of Prajna Yoga and meditation. After more than 5,000 hours of formal training, he can draw on a wide range of skills to address the concerns of his clients while integrating the structure, function and awareness of their mind and body.
 
--Matthew's Full Bio--

Matthew developed an appreciation of the relationship between mind, form, and experience at an early age when he was captivated by traditional mythological stories from all corners of the world. He was first introduced to the teachings of mindfulness and meditation in his early teens when he began to explore the writings of Joseph Campbell. Campbell?s identification of common universal mythic motifs across time and space had a profound influence on his own internal exploration.

Matthew?s first serious foray into the exploration of the body was as a competitive rower when he was introduced to structured yoga practice as a means of maintaining a healthier body. Over many years of strenuous training he accumulated injuries which began to adversely affect his ability to train competitively.

While coaching at M.I.T. he discovered Rolfing® Structural Integration. The impact that Rolfing had on his body was so profound that he decided to study it. During his formal study of the body, he began to delve deeper into the cross relationships between yoga, structural bodywork, and meditation.

In addition to completing his basic and advanced Rolfing® Structural Integration training, Matthew has deepened his knowledge through extensive training in Osteopathy-based Visceral, Vascular, Neural, Cranial and Joint Capsule Manipulation with Jeffrey Burch; Orofacial Myofunctional Therapy; Buteyko Breathing Method; SourcePoint Therapy energy medicine certification; a 500-hour yoga teacher-training certification through Prajna Yoga with Tias and Surya Little; and a 300 hour certification course with Khenpo Samdup Rinpoche on The Stages of Meditation.

Matthew has been fortunate to continue his study of Buddhist philosophy, traditional texts, and practice, in both formal teachings and retreats, primarily under the tutelage of Drupon Ratna Vajra (Rinchen Dorjee) Rinpoche, Garchen Rinpoche, and other highly accomplished Lamas primarily from the Drikung Kagyu lineage of Tibetan Buddhism.
 
Matthew has accumulated more than 5,000 classroom hours studying the body, the mind, and the relationship between the two. He teaches yoga workshops and assists his teachers in their own courses. Weekly, Matthew teaches streaming yoga classes at Yoga Now. For over twenty years Matthew taught and coached rowing to varying age and ability levels in individual, group and clinic settings. He uses all of this experience to help clients learn how to fundamentally change the way that they relate to others, to themselves, to their bodies, and to their world.

Profile:
"I so appreciate your work.  Our sessions are teaching me how to surrender into my body because your touch goes deep, yet feels soft at the same time. It is good for my nervous system to learn I can change without struggle and pain. It wasn't that way in my family.  I also love that you use your intuition in addition to your clinical skills.  In this way we meet as whole person to whole person." ~ Caroline Sabi,  Psychotherapist.
BIOGRAPHY
My love of body knowledge and sincere desire to help alleviate physical suffering have long interwoven to shape my life's work. My first career was as a modern dancer. Because I was not "a natural," I had to study body mechanics and pathways of connectivity very intently to progress. Throughout those years, I traveled from coast to coast to learn dance technique and somatic awareness from renown teachers. Little did I know how much my limitations would later serve my evolution as a bodyworker!

I was introduced to Rolfing toward the end of my dance career.  Excited and inspired, I immediately applied to The Rolf Institute so that I could share the life-affirming benefits and healing power of full-body balance and integration. As Rolfers attend to the body as a whole system, I am committed to ongoing continuing education to better understand the complex interrelationships between different tissues and how to influence them with greater sensitivity. At present I am particularly interested in learning how to communicate more effectively between the body and brain with strategically targeted movement, bodywork, and other forms of input, such as scent, variations in temperature, etc.

I very much enjoy being in a co-creative relationship with my clients. Together we develop sessions which serve your touch preferences and interests. While Rolfing is the strong backbone in my practice, we can draw on multiple modalities to facilitate your accelerated change process and which will empower you to access newly awakened potentials. You will always be the one in charge of what happens in your sessions. Sometimes clients will say "whatever you want to do (at a particular location on their body), Martha." My response is that my only "want" is to honor what your body is telling you. An important part of the healing and transformation process is listening to your sensations and feeling safe to be heard and understood.

Profile:

I am the owner of Structural Energy, and have been in practice since 2004. I received my Advanced certification in 2016. I also hold a BA in Psychology from the University of Minnesota. The mind-body connection is one of my favorite aspects of this work. I genuinely enjoy helping people change and feel better inside and out, and I consider myself to be a sensitive Rolfer®. My clients describe me as being kind, gentle, compassionate, and intuitive.  

I discovered Rolfing soon after I graduated college in 2001, during a very pivotal time in my life. Post 9/11, in between relationships, and processing an overly busy year, I was riddled with anxiety about finding a job in the real world. The more organized my body became with each session, the more organized my mind was. For me, the personal transformation that I had during this process was so profound that it gave me the clarity that Rolfing was what I wanted to pursue as my career path.  

I love building relationships with my clients and supporting them to live a more balanced, pain-free, and better embodied life. Check out my website www.structuralenergy.net for more information on my practice.  I post frequently on my Facebook business page, and you can access that at www.facebook.com/structuralenergy.  Please reach out with any questions, and I look forward to connecting!

Profile:

Thom Shenk is a Certified Advanced Rolfer and Rolf Movement Practitioner. His combined knowledge and understanding of bodywork is eclectic in nature as he assists clients in freeing their bodies from pain, discomfort, tension and the effects of gravity on the body's structure.

Thom insightfully guides his clients to increase and expand their flexibility of movemen and ability to extend in gravity. Their vitality for life, and wholeness of the body, mind, emotions and spirit. He is also a graduate of the Baltimore school of massage and is nationally certified through the NCBTMB and a member of the American Massage Therapy Association.

He is well grounded in the scientific aspects of Rolfing with extensive understanding of anatomy, physiology and kinesiology. His awareness of the systems of the body is intentional. The classes he has taken have taught Thom about the muscles through Massage Therapy, the internal organs through Visceral Manipulation, the nerves through Neurofascial Release, the energy meridians with Jin Shin Jyutsu and the auric/energy body as a Reiki Master and Sekhem healing.

In his work Thom is compassionate, and also combines yearsof knowledge with his intuitive abilities. Thom is supportive of each client's goals for good health. He has also studied Cranio-Sacral Therapy and Matrix Energetics. He has given 60,000 bodywork sessions during his tenure.

Price

A session of Rolfing with Thom costs $115 for an hour and $155 for an hour and a half. There is a $2.50 surcharge added to the regular price for all credit card use. Visa, American Express, Discover and Mastercard are accepted. It is recommended that the sessions not be spaced any further than three weeks apart so the client can receive a sense of continuity and a better awareness of the effect of the Rolfing experience.

Additional Studies

Thom has also extensively studied the metaphysical technologies. He has practiced several forms of meditation since the early 1980's. Namely Zen and Tibetan meditations. He practiced Kundalini Yoga every day for five years and now continues with a weekly practice of yogas. He has familiarity with Yang style Tai Chi and Chi Gung. He began shamanic studies in 1984 and has had the honor of participating in more than 150 sweatlodge ceremonies with Yurock, Karouk, Cree, Lakota, Oglala, Apache, Cherokee, and Tiowa medicine men and women. He has also been on four vision quests.

Congratulations!   You are definitely on the right track to pain relief and feeling better because you are looking for a Certified Rolfer.

Hello, my name is James Donatelli and I am a Chronic Pain and Athletic Performance Specialist. Throughout my decade of experience as a Certified Rolfer, I have witnessed the transformational power of Rolfing in countless individuals who were suffering from persistent pain that hindered their daily activities and enjoyment of life.

In my wellness center which is now located in Hypoluxo, Florida, I have had the privilege of working with a diverse range of clients, including athletes, active individuals, and those who simply want to lead a pain-free and vibrant life. No matter your background or the pain experienced, I believe that everyone deserves the opportunity to live their life to the fullest. As a specialist in chronic pain management, my primary goal is to help my clients alleviate their pain and regain their freedom of movement. As a performance specialist, my next goal is then to help your body perform at an even higher level to meet today's ever increasing demands from family, work and activities. 

For athletes, I understand the importance of optimal performance and recovery. Whether you are a tennis, baseball or soccer player, or any other kind of athlete that involves physical effort and precise movements, I can provide specialized assistance tailored to your specific needs. I am experienced in treating sports-related injuries, improving athletic performance, and helping high-achievers who care about performance up their game and get back on track as quickly as possible.

However, Rolfing is not exclusively for athletes, it simply takes a clear decision and a strong commitment to the program to get better. Many individuals who have been enduring pain for months or even years have found relief through my Rolfing program which is an enhanced 12-session program that combines Rolfing, Cranial Sacral Therapy, Rolf Movement Education, cross-training, nutrition coaching (upon request), and cutting-edge electronic therapies like PEMF or laser treatments (when necessary). I believe in a comprehensive holistic approach to healing, addressing not only the physical aspects of the pain but also the emotional and energetic components as well. This program is custom tailored to address your specific needs and to ensure that you receive safe, effective, and long-lasting results.

My commitment to all my clients' well-being extends beyond the treatment sessions. I prioritize education and empowerment, equipping my clients with the knowledge and tools they need to continue their progress independently. Whether you are an athlete striving for peak performance or an individual seeking to enhance your energy and overall quality of life, I am dedicated to helping you achieve your goals.

Choosing the right Certified Rolfer is crucial, as it requires trust and a personal connection. If my approach resonates with you and aligns with your needs and aspirations, I invite you to schedule a consultation. Together, we can embark on a journey towards a pain-free and vibrant life.

In conclusion, as a Certified Rolfer specializing in chronic pain and athletic performance, I am committed to helping my clients overcome pain, improve their energy levels, and enhance their quality of life. From professional athletes to individuals seeking relief from long-standing pain, I offer a tailor-made 12-session program that combine various techniques and therapies for effective and lasting results. If you are in search of a health provider who can guide you towards a pain-free and vibrant life, I encourage you to fill out the goals and outcomes questionnaire on my website so we can then discuss your specific goals and needs and how my program can serve you. 

Working with me you can expect to:

  • Reduce chronic pain,
  • Improve posture, balance and flexibility,
  • Feel stronger and more grounded,
  • Reduce recovery time between workouts,
  • Reduce chronic inflammation, 
  • Slow the aging process,
  • Reduce scar tissue adhesions after injuries or surgeries (if any),
  • Straighten scoliotic curves in the spine (if any),
  • Strengthen hips, knees, feet and ankles,
  • Dramatically reduce chances of future athletic injuries. 


If this looks, sounds or feels like possible fit for you, please visit my website at  www.DonatelliWellness.com to fill out the questionnaire.  You will then get a FREE, 15-min Telephone Consultation to discuss how my custom-tailored Rolfing program can help you. 

To Your Future Health, Wealth and Performance!

Profile:

As a Rolfer, I align and refine the body's relationship to gravity. I have found this work to have very profound effects on both the self and body. Rolfing is renowned for its restorative ability, it is also great for working with overuse repetitive stain injuries, pain management as well as injury prevention.

Believing each person's structure is unique, I work with everyone differently. I feel each person can find health within their own body type. My approach is to renew balance through Rolfing Structural Integration and Rolf Movement. I often combine these approaches in each session.

I see Rolfing Structural Integration as a terrific way to enliven the body and release adhesions and locked tissues. I use Rolf Movement as a tool to renew spatial perceptions. Rolf Movement gives more awareness and connection in how to move with greater grace and ease. Rolfing renews the natural balance for an individual, allowing each person to further define or reinvent relationships to his or her body and environment. I enjoy seeing the transformation that takes place as people become more empowered in their bodies. You are welcome to take a look at elementalrolfing.com for additional information. Please contact me to make an appointment.

Lu is seeing clients primarily for first assessments to determine the best way to go forward. Since she now lives mainly in Boulder, CO, as an 
instructor at the Dr. Ida Rolf Institute, she can also offer mentoring for colleagues in the Denver/Boulder areas. 

3333 Iris Ave, Boulder, CO 80301 is her practice address in Boulder.

Housecalls are definitely possible and ideal for families. Office visits depend on location and ability -- Lu travels around for mentoring sessions
and can see clients at colleagues' practices.

Her career in alternative medicine in Germany was a naturopathic physician where Lu was successfully treating chronic painful conditions
in the musculoskeletal system already before coming to the Dr. Ida Rolf Institute in 2006. 

Her ambition to help her patients further led her to Being in Balance® Movement Exercises for better posture, balance and coordination as well as more strength, flexibility and range of motion.

Lu came to the US in 2006 to study Rolfing Structural Integration, has been a Certified Rolfer since 2007, and a Certified Advanced Rolfer since 2016. 

In her treatments and consultations Lu makes use of her extensive education and experience in order to achieve permanent changes in her client's posture and movement -
towards not only a painfree, but an overall healthier life.

At Balance Orlando, her colleagues refer clients with difficult health conditions to Lu for at least a "First Visit" or to determine whether Rolfing is the best strategy. 

Lu visits her friends and community in Orlando every 2-3 months for a few days, and during those times she is available at www.balanceorlando.com, the

Congratulations!   You are definitely on the right track to pain relief and feeling better because you are looking for a Certified Rolfer.

Hello, my name is James Donatelli and I am a Chronic Pain and Athletic Performance Specialist. Throughout my decade of experience as a Certified Rolfer, I have witnessed the transformational power of Rolfing in countless individuals who were suffering from persistent pain that hindered their daily activities and enjoyment of life.

In my wellness center which is now located in Hypoluxo, Florida, I have had the privilege of working with a diverse range of clients, including athletes, active individuals, and those who simply want to lead a pain-free and vibrant life. No matter your background or the pain experienced, I believe that everyone deserves the opportunity to live their life to the fullest. As a specialist in chronic pain management, my primary goal is to help my clients alleviate their pain and regain their freedom of movement. As a performance specialist, my next goal is then to help your body perform at an even higher level to meet today's ever increasing demands from family, work and activities. 

For athletes, I understand the importance of optimal performance and recovery. Whether you are a tennis, baseball or soccer player, or any other kind of athlete that involves physical effort and precise movements, I can provide specialized assistance tailored to your specific needs. I am experienced in treating sports-related injuries, improving athletic performance, and helping high-achievers who care about performance up their game and get back on track as quickly as possible.

However, Rolfing is not exclusively for athletes, it simply takes a clear decision and a strong commitment to the program to get better. Many individuals who have been enduring pain for months or even years have found relief through my Rolfing program which is an enhanced 12-session program that combines Rolfing, Cranial Sacral Therapy, Rolf Movement Education, cross-training, nutrition coaching (upon request), and cutting-edge electronic therapies like PEMF or laser treatments (when necessary). I believe in a comprehensive holistic approach to healing, addressing not only the physical aspects of the pain but also the emotional and energetic components as well. This program is custom tailored to address your specific needs and to ensure that you receive safe, effective, and long-lasting results.

My commitment to all my clients' well-being extends beyond the treatment sessions. I prioritize education and empowerment, equipping my clients with the knowledge and tools they need to continue their progress independently. Whether you are an athlete striving for peak performance or an individual seeking to enhance your energy and overall quality of life, I am dedicated to helping you achieve your goals.

Choosing the right Certified Rolfer is crucial, as it requires trust and a personal connection. If my approach resonates with you and aligns with your needs and aspirations, I invite you to schedule a consultation. Together, we can embark on a journey towards a pain-free and vibrant life.

In conclusion, as a Certified Rolfer specializing in chronic pain and athletic performance, I am committed to helping my clients overcome pain, improve their energy levels, and enhance their quality of life. From professional athletes to individuals seeking relief from long-standing pain, I offer a tailor-made 12-session program that combine various techniques and therapies for effective and lasting results. If you are in search of a health provider who can guide you towards a pain-free and vibrant life, I encourage you to fill out the goals and outcomes questionnaire on my website so we can then discuss your specific goals and needs and how my program can serve you. 

Working with me you can expect to:

  • Reduce chronic pain,
  • Improve posture, balance and flexibility,
  • Feel stronger and more grounded,
  • Reduce recovery time between workouts,
  • Reduce chronic inflammation, 
  • Slow the aging process,
  • Reduce scar tissue adhesions after injuries or surgeries (if any),
  • Straighten scoliotic curves in the spine (if any),
  • Strengthen hips, knees, feet and ankles,
  • Dramatically reduce chances of future athletic injuries. 


If this looks, sounds or feels like possible fit for you, please visit my website at  www.DonatelliWellness.com to fill out the questionnaire.  You will then get a FREE, 15-min Telephone Consultation to discuss how my custom-tailored Rolfing program can help you. 

To Your Future Health, Wealth and Performance!


James J Donatelli
Chronic Pain Specialist, Certified Rolfer, Certified Rolf Movement Practitioner, Posture Alignment Specialist, Cranial Sacral Therapist, Certified Corporate Wellness Specialist, Latin Dance Instructor, Tony Robbins Sr Leader, Advanced Nutrition Coach, Cross-training Coach.

Profile:

Heidi Massa (BA, JD, University of Chicago),  Certified Advanced Rolfer and Rolf Movement Practitoner, has guided the somatic adventures of the discerning, the curious and the brave since 1994 in Chicago's East Lincoln Park.  She's a function-oriented practitioner; and her client-centered approach is tailored to meet your particular needs, interests, and way of being in the world -- not to conform to any particular viewpoint.  You can expect:

  • Fun, challenge and discovery
  • Exploring questions you might never have asked before
  • Access to real options you might not have thought possible

In-person consultations are always free of charge.

 

Heidi trained through the Rolf Institute in Munich, Germany and Sao Paulo, Brazil:

  • Certified Advanced Rolfer 2000
  • Rolf Movement Practitioner 1995
  • Certified   Rolfer 1994

 

Continuing Education: Heidi studied extensively with Hubert Godard over several years to learn the strategies and techniques of his game-changing theory of tonic function. In addition to using the tonic function approach in movement sessions, Heidi makes it a key component of her structural sessions, movement awareness being essential to recognizing, using and maintaining changes made through hands-on work.  Heidi has additional specialized training in other topics, including:

  • Biomechanics of limbs and axial complex
  • Berry® Method
  • Move in Mind®
  • Tensegrity Touch
  • Osteopathic approaches to low back pain
  • Cranial, neural and visceral work
  • Interventions with oral reflex functions

 

Professional Activities: Heidi has served on the Rolf Institute's Ethics & Business Practices Committee since 1997; worked with its Law & Legislation Committee for several years following its inception in 2007; and acted as an editor for the Journal of Structural Integration since 2001. Member, ISMETA (International Somatic movement Education & Therapy Ass'n).

  In 1994 Bruce Schonfeld was Certified as a Certified Rolfer and Rolfing Movement Integration Teacher through the combined studies program at the Rolf Institute of Structural Integration (RISI). Bruce has studied extensively with three of Dr. Rolf's teachers including Jim Asher, Michael Salveson, and Jan Sultan. Bruce has taken the RISI Advanced Rolfing Training three times. Through RISI, Bruce co-taught Unit 1 with Mary Bond and Unit 2 with Jane Harrington. Profile:

 

In 1994 Bruce Schonfeld was Certified as a Certified Rolfer and Rolfing Movement Integration Teacher through the combined studies program at the Rolf Institute of Structural Integration (RISI). Bruce has studied extensively with three of Dr. Rolf's teachers including Jim Asher, Michael Salveson, and Jan Sultan. Bruce has taken the RISI Advanced Rolfing Training three times. Through RISI, Bruce co-taught Unit 1 with Mary Bond and Unit 2 with Jane Harrington. Bruce has assisted the RISI Advanced Rolfing Training with Jan Sultan and Michael Salveson. Bruce has studied Visceral Mobilization with Certified Advanced Rolfers Jan Sultan, Christoph Sommer, Peter Schwind, Jeffrey Maitland, and Liz Gaggini. Between 2017-2018, Jan Sultan and Bruce Schonfeld co-taught all three courses in Structural-Visceral Integration. Bruce is the developer of Structural-Visceral Integration | Fascial Integration bridging the musculoskeletal and visceral systems. CE emphasizes clinical reasoning, troubleshooting, and manual therapy technique. He teaches domestically and internationally.

Bruce has studied Visceral Osteopathy and Visceral Manipulation Technique extensively since 1996 including 300+ hours directly with Jean-Pierre Barral DO. Bruce has studied VM with Alain Croibier DO, Didier Prat DO, Alain Gehin DO, Claudia Kohn DO, Olivier Bazin DO, A.J. de Koning DO, Marc Naudin DO, Rene Assink DO, Bonnie Gintis DO, Mark Bookhout PT, Dee Ahern PT, and has assisted VM extensively with Gail Wetzler PT. Bruce has assisted Judy Russell PT and Peter Coppola PT with the Barral Institute's Visceral Dissection classes for many years.  

Bruce is an Approved Continuing Education (CE) Provider for the Rolf Institute Of Structural Integration (RISI), the International Association of Structural Integrators (IASI) and the International Association of Healthcare Educators (IAHE). He has also taught classes at Yo San University and Emperors College Of Traditional Oriental Medicine in Los Angeles California as well as at the Oregon College of Oriental Medicine (OCOM). He is an Approved Continuing Education Provider through the California State Board of Acupuncturists teaching Skills in Structural Integration, Fascial Manipulation and Body Analysis. Bruce taught a 'Skills In Structural Integration' manual therapy series at IPSB, in Los Angeles, for over a decade. Bruce has trained in and studied the movement art called Continuum extensively with the founder Emilie Conrad, Susan Harper, Barbara Mindell, Gael Ohlgren, and others. Bruce was a Jungle Gym Teacher at the Continuum Studio in Santa Monica and taught his original series of Movement Carnival classes. Bruce has completed the yearlong Bodynamics Developmental Psychology foundation training with Anne and Joel Isaacs. Bruce has studied somatic psychology, attended supervision classes, and worked clinically with Somatic Experiencing (SE) developer Peter Levine PhD during his experimental hands-on phase in Boulder in the early - mid 1990's. 

Bruce is an Independent Documentary Filmmaker who is the Director and Producer of The Secret Life of Fascia. Part 1 receivedLlaurels and the honor of Official Selection to the 6th Annual Raw Science Film Festival. Part 1 of hte Docuseries is currently available at https://vimeo.com/ondemand/secretlifeoffascia

Bruce maintains a private practice in Los Angeles California (Sundance Physical Therapy 2212 Pico Boulevard, Santa Monica CA, 90405) working both inside and outside the recipe. Bruce primarily works with clients in two different scenarios. (i) The first is the classic '10-Series Recipe' wherein the strategy is global, addresses the whole body, and that of the Generalist. The 10-Series Recipe approach does not primarily focus on the client's symptomatic issues/areas as its main agenda, rather the objective of the recipe is to not miss the forest for the trees, think systemically, and address the whole body. It seeks to work with the whole person and balance the whole body. (ii) The second scenario focuses on addressing people's orthopedic and/or pain problems more specifically. Often the focus is on regional anatomy related to the local issue. Bruce specializes in troubleshooting and problem solving tricky pain and orthopedic problems from structural, functional, and biopsychosocial perspectives. 

Please contact Bruce directly or through his website for additional information about his practice and/or continuing education class offerings at www.advancedrolfing.com

Dan has successfully helped a wide variety of individuals positively improve their embodied lives and spirits since commencing his full-time practice as a body-centered therapist after graduating from the Dr. Ida Rolf Institute in Boulder, Colorado in 1990.  Dan completed his Advanced Rolfing® Certification with the European Rolfing Association in Rome, Italy in 1996.

Dan is a Licensed Social Worker (LSW) and a Licensed Addictions Counselor (LAC) with specialization in Motivational Interviewing and Cognitive Behavioral Therapy.  Dan is a Licensed Acupuncture Detox Specialist (LADS). Dan is a graduate of the Professional Skills Training program of the Hakomi Method of Body Centered Psychotherapy.  Dan is a Certified CranioSacral Therapist (CST), a Certified Visceral Manipulation Practitioner and a Indiana State Certified Massage Therapist (CMT). Dan is a frequent and regular teaching assistant at the Upledger CranioSacral and the Barral Visceral Manipulation trainings and leads a Visceral Manipulation study group, sanctioned by the Barral Institute, for professional practitioners. Dan successfully completed a post-graduate certification program at the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor in Sex Therapy and Sex Education in 2018.  Dan is CPR certified through the American Red Cross. Dan is a member in good standing the Dr. Ida Rolf Institute (DIRI), the Associated Massage and Bodywork Professionals (AMBP), the Internationsl Association of Healthcare Practitioners (IAHP), the United States Association for Body Psychotherapy (USABP) and the American Association of Sex Educators, Counselors and Therapists (AASECT). Dan currently sits on the Board of Directors for the Dr.Ida Rolf Institute.

With over 30 years of full time practice, I have helped thousands of people to stand taller, breathe fuller and move more gracefully.  I have helped many people who suffer from a wide variety of complaints feel less pain and more joy and freedom.  If you desire positive changes in your life, I invite you to contact me directly. I would love the opportunity to work with you.

Haven Johnson is overjoyed to bring Rolfing back to Eastern Oregon. She is passionate about guiding clients into curiosity about their own bodies. Before approaching the Rolfing path, Haven was pursuing a sociology degree. This lent itself to her development of a deep interest in language, how language itself is limited in describing phenomena we experience, and how our habitual usage of language creates our understanding of our existence. While Rolfing often lends itself to clients finding relief from pain and achieving greater alignment in their relationship to gravity, Haven is excited about the work that happens in self-awareness and belief. She is guided by the question - What else is possible?

Profile:

Brian Marchese is a Phi Beta Kappa graduate in Philosophy from Connecticut's Wesleyan University, where he examined the neglect of the body in Western thought.

His passion for running and racing as a 12-year member of the Central Park Track Club in NYC led him to complete twelve marathons but also to a growing litany of injuries that worsened into his thirties, until a herniated disk in his back forced him to leave long-distance running. After a long and frustrating search for a modality that could address not only his injuries, but, more importantly, the need for both resilience and balance to break the injury cycle, he discovered Rolfing?. It worked!

Brian entered the program at The Rolf Institute? of Structural Integration in Boulder, Colorado and completed his clinical work through the European Rolfing? Association in Munich, Germany in 2002. In 2005, he graduated with Advanced certification in Boulder. Today, he remains dedicated to lifelong learning, with continued studies ranging from spinal and pelvic mechanics to methods of functional integration, visceral manipulation to cranial-sacral.

Inspired in part by his own athletic pursuits and those of his clients, Brian has a particular eye for the relationship between structure and function. In 2006, he completed his Rolf Movement? certification. At the well-respected Pilates Chicago studio, he went through the Pilates instructor training program in 2010. While he keeps up his own running mileage, he has learned through the years to complement it more wisely with well-rounded functional training. His ongoing inquiry into what a fluid, enlivening, and evolving experience of embodiment can mean has led him to dive deeply into approaches to movement such as Pilates, yoga, Gyrotonic?, TRX Suspension Training? and RedCord. He has been known to brave even the female-dominated Bar Method arena in order to investigate the structural-functional challenges being faced by a particular client.

Brian?s interests include working with special populations. He was an assistant in the Motion Analysis Center at Chicago?s Children?s Memorial Hospital, which focuses on pre- and post-operative gait analysis of children with neuromuscular disorders. He was also a Rolfer-in-residence at the Shake-A-Leg, Inc summer residential alternative therapy program then located in Newport, RI for people with spinal cord injuries, stroke, cerebral palsy, and traumatic brain injury.

Profile:
Jen Wenz Somatics is the private practice of Jen Wenz, MDiv, Certifed Rolfer©, including: Rolfing© Structural Integration: bodywork and movement integration for healing and high performance; Ritual Officiation and Ceremony Design: weddings, baby welcomings, and other life transitions; and Somatic Coaching: embodied healing and transformation for joyful, equitable relationships in action. 

Jen started Jen Wenz Somatics to offer support, accompaniment, and skill to clients as they navigate the changes in their lives and become more fully who they are. In all of her work, she collaborates with clients to explore these changes and discover what’s available and what they long for within them. Whether the changes are due to aging, injury, surgery, pregnancy, trauma, chronic pain, oppressive systems, or a desired major life transition, she supports clients to move with change toward greater balance, ease, trust, and possibility. 

Jen's approach to Rolfing is adaptable, aware, and collaborative; trauma-informed, joyful, and transformational. She loves to support clients in accessing the freedom that comes through a deeper felt sense of safety, support and possibility in their bodies. Her intention is for her clients to leave empowered with new options, able to show up in their lives more aware, embodied, on purpose, and ready to build the world they long for.

Profile:

Isaac is a Certified Advanced Rolfer©, National Academy of Sports Medicine Certified Personal Trainer, National Academy of Sports Medicine Corrective Exercise Specialist, Certified XPT Coach, Certified Functional Range Conditioning Specialist, and Licensed Massage Therapist. He has had a full-time practice focusing on posture and pain relief for over 20+ years. His experience in Massage Therapy, Structural Integration, and movement work allow him to uniquely combine modalities to help people free themselves from chronic pain, improve athletic performance, and address posture/movement compensations.

In addition to his full time practice, he has taught classes in the Rolf Method of Structural Integration for The Guild of Structural Integration and Posture Alignment Therapy for Egoscue Institute. He is also the inventor of SqrShot, a tripod adapter for tablets and smart phones, that works with his app, Body Align Pro®. Isaac created the app to help practitioners document changes in their client?s progress including posture, range of motion and weight loss.

Having had chronic low back pain, headaches, and neck pain for over a decade Isaac has freed himself from pain with the techniques of posture therapy and has been pain free since.

Isaac lives in Santa Barbara with his wife, their two children, and dogs.

Profile:

Kevin Frank has been a Rolfer since 1987. He is certified as an Advanced Rolfer, a Movement Practitioner and is a Rolf Movement Instructor at the Rolf Institute. He is the co-author (with Caryn McHose) of How Life Moves, Explorations in Meaning and Body Awareness, North Atlantic, 2006, and has authored numerous articles about working with perception and coordination in the context of Structural Integration which can be found at, and downloaded from, www.resourcesinmovement.com under "article archive."

Kevin has worked extensively in Continuum movement and Susan Harper's perceptual trainings, Hubert Godard's tonic function studies, Caryn McHose's experiential anatomy curricula,. He also helped to establish the Springwater Center for Meditative Inquiry in Springwater, NY, having been a student of Toni Packer at the Rochester Zen Center, in Rochester, NY.
Kevin lives in central NH and is co-founder of Resources in Movement, a center for somatic inquiry and Structural Integration.

Kevin advocates positing Structural Integration as a field of inquiry for lasting changes in coordination. Posture is an example of coordination. From this premise, fascial manipulation is an effective way to inform the brain's action and sensory maps. Thus, SI becomes congruent with the established studies in motor control and neuroscience. SI education is most effective when it emphasizes embodiment and a broad range of perceptive and coordinative skills that are linked to Rolf's classic recipe

  In 1994 Bruce Schonfeld was Certified as a Certified Rolfer and Rolfing Movement Integration Teacher through the combined studies program at the Rolf Institute of Structural Integration (RISI). Bruce has studied extensively with three of Dr. Rolf's teachers including Jim Asher, Michael Salveson, and Jan Sultan. Bruce has taken the RISI Advanced Rolfing Training three times. Through RISI, Bruce co-taught Unit 1 with Mary Bond and Unit 2 with Jane Harrington. Read More...
Profile:

In 1994 Bruce Schonfeld was Certified as a Certified Rolfer and Rolfing Movement Integration Teacher through the combined studies program at the Rolf Institute of Structural Integration (RISI). Bruce has studied extensively with three of Dr. Rolf's teachers including Jim Asher, Michael Salveson, and Jan Sultan. Bruce has taken the RISI Advanced Rolfing Training three times. Through RISI, Bruce co-taught Unit 1 with Mary Bond and Unit 2 with Jane Harrington. Bruce has assisted the RISI Advanced Rolfing Training with Jan Sultan and Michael Salveson. Bruce has studied Visceral Mobilization with Certified Advanced Rolfers Jan Sultan, Christoph Sommer, Peter Schwind, Jeffrey Maitland, and Liz Gaggini. Between 2017-2018, Jan Sultan and Bruce Schonfeld co-taught all three courses in Structural-Visceral Integration. Bruce is the developer of Structural-Visceral Integration | Fascial Integration bridging the musculoskeletal and visceral systems. CE emphasizes clinical reasoning, troubleshooting, and manual therapy technique. He teaches domestically and internationally.

Bruce has studied Visceral Osteopathy and Visceral Manipulation Technique extensively since 1996 including 300+ hours directly with Jean-Pierre Barral DO. Bruce has studied VM with Alain Croibier DO, Didier Prat DO, Alain Gehin DO, Claudia Kohn DO, Olivier Bazin DO, A.J. de Koning DO, Marc Naudin DO, Rene Assink DO, Bonnie Gintis DO, Mark Bookhout PT, Dee Ahern PT, and has assisted VM extensively with Gail Wetzler PT. Bruce has assisted Judy Russell PT and Peter Coppola PT with the Barral Institute's Visceral Dissection classes for many years.  

Bruce is an Approved Continuing Education (CE) Provider for the Rolf Institute Of Structural Integration (RISI), the International Association of Structural Integrators (IASI) and the International Association of Healthcare Educators (IAHE). He has also taught classes at Yo San University and Emperors College Of Traditional Oriental Medicine in Los Angeles California as well as at the Oregon College of Oriental Medicine (OCOM). He is an Approved Continuing Education Provider through the California State Board of Acupuncturists teaching Skills in Structural Integration, Fascial Manipulation and Body Analysis. Bruce taught a 'Skills In Structural Integration' manual therapy series at IPSB, in Los Angeles, for over a decade. Bruce has trained in and studied the movement art called Continuum extensively with the founder Emilie Conrad, Susan Harper, Barbara Mindell, Gael Ohlgren, and others. Bruce was a Jungle Gym Teacher at the Continuum Studio in Santa Monica and taught his original series of Movement Carnival classes. Bruce has completed the yearlong Bodynamics Developmental Psychology foundation training with Anne and Joel Isaacs. Bruce has studied somatic psychology, attended supervision classes, and worked clinically with Somatic Experiencing (SE) developer Peter Levine PhD during his experimental hands-on phase in Boulder in the early - mid 1990's. 

Bruce is an Independent Documentary Filmmaker who is the Director and Producer of The Secret Life of Fascia. Part 1 receivedLlaurels and the honor of Official Selection to the 6th Annual Raw Science Film Festival. Part 1 of hte Docuseries is currently available at https://vimeo.com/ondemand/secretlifeoffascia

Bruce maintains a private practice in Los Angeles California (Sundance Physical Therapy 2212 Pico Boulevard, Santa Monica CA, 90405) working both inside and outside the recipe. Bruce primarily works with clients in two different scenarios. (i) The first is the classic '10-Series Recipe' wherein the strategy is global, addresses the whole body, and that of the Generalist. The 10-Series Recipe approach does not primarily focus on the client's symptomatic issues/areas as its main agenda, rather the objective of the recipe is to not miss the forest for the trees, think systemically, and address the whole body. It seeks to work with the whole person and balance the whole body. (ii) The second scenario focuses on addressing people's orthopedic and/or pain problems more specifically. Often the focus is on regional anatomy related to the local issue. Bruce specializes in troubleshooting and problem solving tricky pain and orthopedic problems from structural, functional, and biopsychosocial perspectives. 

Please contact Bruce directly or through his website for additional information about his practice and/or continuing education class offerings at www.advancedrolfing.com

Profile:

As a Rolfer, I align and refine the body's relationship to gravity. I have found this work to have very profound effects on both the self and body. Rolfing is renowned for its restorative ability, it is also great for working with overuse repetitive stain injuries, pain management as well as injury prevention.

Believing each person's structure is unique, I work with everyone differently. I feel each person can find health within their own body type. My approach is to renew balance through Rolfing Structural Integration and Rolf Movement. I often combine these approaches in each session.

I see Rolfing Structural Integration as a terrific way to enliven the body and release adhesions and locked tissues. I use Rolf Movement as a tool to renew spatial perceptions. Rolf Movement gives more awareness and connection in how to move with greater grace and ease. Rolfing renews the natural balance for an individual, allowing each person to further define or reinvent relationships to his or her body and environment. I enjoy seeing the transformation that takes place as people become more empowered in their bodies. You are welcome to take a look at elementalrolfing.com for additional information. Please contact me to make an appointment.

Profile:

My goal is to create ease in movement for all bodies.  As a Rolfer and movement educator, I understand how to facilitate restoration and maximum potential in a body, and I aim to share my experience to enable others on their own journeys toward ease. 

I work with clients to relieve injuries, harmful and painful postural habits, and movement restrictions through specialized manual therapy and movement analysis. Through this integrative approach, the body can now operate with a healthier pattern of function and balance.

At an early age I developed an understanding of the body's need for structural integrity without strain through my ballet and modern dance training. I also gained an appreciation for the kind of care and attention the body requires in order to live comfortably and to prevent injury.  

I discovered Rolfing Structural Integration when my body had become painful and unmanageable despite my best efforts at self-care. Rolfing helped me develop a whole new level of potential and ease in my body that I never knew was possible.  

I believe that all bodies have the potential for ease in movement regardless of medical history or physical fitness and it can be found through a journey of transformation.

Office locations in Lower Fairfield County, Connecticut and New York City.

Member of the International Association of Structural Integrators (IASI) & the Dr. Ida Rolf Institute® (DIRI).

The Female Pelvis and Cycles of Life with Tom Myers & Dr. Eden Fromberg, 2017

Anterior Neck and Cranial Base with Ron Murray, DO, 2016

Source Point Therapy: Module 2 with Bob Shrei and Donna Thomson, 2015

Respiratory Diaphragm, Ribs and Embryonic Midline with Ron Murray, DO, 2015

Source Point Therapy: Module 1 with Bob Shrei, 2015

Yoga Alliance: Registered Yoga Teacher, 2012

Merce Cunningham Dance Studio: Professional Training Program, 2001-2007

Bard College: Bachelor of Arts in Dance and Choreography, 1998-2002

and can see clients at colleagues' practices.

Her career in alternative medicine in Germany was a naturopathic physician where Lu was successfully treating chronic painful conditions
in the musculoskeletal system already before coming to the Dr. Ida Rolf Institute in 2006. 

Her ambition to help her patients further led her to Being in Balance® Movement Exercises for better posture, balance and coordination as well as more strength, flexibility and range of motion.

Lu came to the US in 2006 to study Rolfing Structural Integration, has been a Certified Rolfer since 2007, and a Certified Advanced Rolfer since 2016. 

In her treatments and consultations Lu makes use of her extensive education and experience in order to achieve permanent changes in her client's posture and movement -
towards not only a painfree, but an overall healthier life.

At Balance Orlando, her colleagues refer clients with difficult health conditions to Lu for at least a "First Visit" or to determine whether Rolfing is the best strategy. 

Lu visits her friends and community in Orlando every 2-3 months for a few days, and during those times she is available at www.balanceorlando.com, the 
manual therapy clinic she founded in 2008.      Direct link to schedule: www.balanceorlandoschedule.info  407 704 8867   calls get text message follow-up if receptionists

Profile:

Years of chronic low back pain brought me as a client to Rolfing? Structural Integration.? When I experienced results such as complete relief from my back pain, increased body awareness, and increased self esteem, I decided to pursue a career as a Certified Rolfer.  Rolfing has also helped me to recover from two motor vehicle accidents and has kept my body free and limber to support me in physical activity.? Rolfing SI has also been an incredible healing modality for my entire family.

I have had to fortune to study with a few first generation Rolfers who trained directly under Dr. Rolf such as Jan Sultan and Sharon Wheeler. Additionally, I have studied Craniosacral Therapy and Lymph Drainage Therapy, two osteopathic techniques which can be used to support the goals of Rolfing Structural Integration. ?More recently I have seen my practice transform as I have incorporated Neural Mobilization techniques to release tissue in deep and profound ways.

I believe that the crux of my work is a partnership with you and your body. ?In a way similiar to a midwife facilating a natural process like birth I see Rolfers as facilitating another natural process in the body: Integration or Self-Organization of the body. ?We do much more than just releasing tight or strained tissues; we help to get those tissues and parts of the body working together to bring greater balance to the whole. ?This experience varies from person to person, but it is common to hear reports of "lightness" and "easiness" in the body.?

I would be glad to talk with you in person about your goals and how Rolfing? Structural Integration may help.

"I so appreciate your work.  Our sessions are teaching me how to surrender into my body because your touch goes deep, yet feels soft at the same time. It is good for my nervous system to learn I can change without struggle and pain. It wasn't that way in my family.  I also love that you use your intuition in addition to your clinical skills.  In this way we meet as whole person to whole person." ~ Caroline Sabi,  Psychotherapist.

BIOGRAPHY

My love of body knowledge and sincere desire to help alleviate physical suffering have long interwoven to shape my life's work. My first career was as a modern dancer. Because I was not "a natural," I had to study body mechanics and pathways of connectivity very intently to progress. Throughout those years, I traveled from coast to coast to learn dance technique and somatic awareness from renown teachers. Little did I know how much my limitations would later serve my evolution as a bodyworker!

I was introduced to Rolfing toward the end of my dance career.  Excited and inspired, I immediately applied to The Rolf Institute so that I could share the life-affirming benefits and healing power of full-body balance and integration. As Rolfers attend to the body as a whole system, I am committed to ongoing continuing education to better understand the complex interrelationships between different tissues and how to influence them with greater sensitivity. At present I am particularly interested in learning how to communicate more effectively between the body and brain with strategically targeted movement, bodywork, and other forms of input, such as scent, variations in temperature, etc.

I very much enjoy being in a co-creative relationship with my clients. Together we develop sessions which serve your touch preferences and interests. While Rolfing is the strong backbone in my practice, we can draw on multiple modalities to facilitate your accelerated change process and which will empower you to access newly awakened potentials. You will always be the one in charge of what happens in your sessions. Sometimes clients will say "whatever you want to do (at a particular location on their body), Martha." My response is that my only "want" is to honor what your body is telling you. An important part of the healing and transformation process is listening to your sensations and feeling safe to be heard and understood.

As a Certified Advanced Rolfer  with over 20 years experience, I combine structural understanding and anatomical knowledge with an open-minded intuitive approach to help transform the human body.  Since the beginning of my career I have dedicated a great deal of time to advancing my skills with additional training in Visceral Manipulation and Biomechanics.  Visceral Manipulation is based on the principle that all organs have an inherent motion and necessary range of motion; any res

Profile:

As a Certified Advanced Rolfer with over 20 years experience, I combine structural understanding and anatomical knowledge with an open-minded intuitive approach to help transform the human body.  Since the beginning of my career I have dedicated a great deal of time to advancing my skills with additional training in Visceral Manipulation and Biomechanics.  Visceral Manipulation is based on the principle that all organs have an inherent motion and necessary range of motion; any restriction to an organ results in a misalignment in the skeletal-muscular body. The physiology of each organ is dependent on its range of motion within the visceral cavity. Biomechanics allows one to identify and determine how to correct asymmetries in the body. As we experience large or small injuries in life, our body seeks to adapt by either exaggerating these irregularities or driving individual body parts out of pattern. As a Rolfer I seek to engage these asymmetries in the body to determine there driving force.

In addition to my private practice, I have been an instructor in the Rolf Institute?s Phase I: Foundations of Rolfing Structural Integration in Boulder. As a Class room teacher I encourage students to build a strong framework of science theory and philosophy of Rolfing and to explore and master these concepts through personal exploration. As a mentor to students in the Rolf training process, I provide one-on-one teaching experience using a comfortable and highly attentive teaching style of learning, whether that's by allowing students to struggle through problems on their own, or by giving students as much or as little feedback on Rolfing techniques, as required.

I maintain a private practice with normal working days that include Thurday through Sunday. My sessions last about an hour and fifteen minutes and cost $160. per session. I accept cash, check and credit cards. For an Appointment call 720-276-1972 or click website to book an appointment today.

I am happy to visit with you at my office to answer questions and demonstrate what my work feels like during a 30-minute no-charge consultation.

Please contact me with questions or to set up an appointment.

Congratulations!   You are definitely on the right track to pain relief and feeling better because you are looking for a Certified Rolfer.

Hello, my name is James Donatelli and I am a Chronic Pain and Athletic Performance Specialist. Throughout my decade of experience as a Certified Rolfer, I have witnessed the transformational power of Rolfing in countless individuals who were suffering from persistent pain that hindered their daily activities and enjoyment of life.

In my wellness center which is now located in Hypoluxo, Florida, I have had the privilege of working with a diverse range of clients, including athletes, active individuals, and those who simply want to lead a pain-free and vibrant life. No matter your background or the pain experienced, I believe that everyone deserves the opportunity to live their life to the fullest. As a specialist in chronic pain management, my primary goal is to help my clients alleviate their pain and regain their freedom of movement. As a performance specialist, my next goal is then to help your body perform at an even higher level to meet today's ever increasing demands from family, work and activities. 

For athletes, I understand the importance of optimal performance and recovery. Whether you are a tennis, baseball or soccer player, or any other kind of athlete that involves physical effort and precise movements, I can provide specialized assistance tailored to your specific needs. I am experienced in treating sports-related injuries, improving athletic performance, and helping high-achievers who care about performance up their game and get back on track as quickly as possible.

However, Rolfing is not exclusively for athletes, it simply takes a clear decision and a strong commitment to the program to get better. Many individuals who have been enduring pain for months or even years have found relief through my Rolfing program which is an enhanced 12-session program that combines Rolfing, Cranial Sacral Therapy, Rolf Movement Education, cross-training, nutrition coaching (upon request), and cutting-edge electronic therapies like PEMF or laser treatments (when necessary). I believe in a comprehensive holistic approach to healing, addressing not only the physical aspects of the pain but also the emotional and energetic components as well. This program is custom tailored to address your specific needs and to ensure that you receive safe, effective, and long-lasting results.

My commitment to all my clients' well-being extends beyond the treatment sessions. I prioritize education and empowerment, equipping my clients with the knowledge and tools they need to continue their progress independently. Whether you are an athlete striving for peak performance or an individual seeking to enhance your energy and overall quality of life, I am dedicated to helping you achieve your goals.

Choosing the right Certified Rolfer is crucial, as it requires trust and a personal connection. If my approach resonates with you and aligns with your needs and aspirations, I invite you to schedule a consultation. Together, we can embark on a journey towards a pain-free and vibrant life.

In conclusion, as a Certified Rolfer specializing in chronic pain and athletic performance, I am committed to helping my clients overcome pain, improve their energy levels, and enhance their quality of life. From professional athletes to individuals seeking relief from long-standing pain, I offer a tailor-made 12-session program that combine various techniques and therapies for effective and lasting results. If you are in search of a health provider who can guide you towards a pain-free and vibrant life, I encourage you to fill out the goals and outcomes questionnaire on my website so we can then discuss your specific goals and needs and how my program can serve you. 

Working with me you can expect to:

  • Reduce chronic pain,
  • Improve posture, balance and flexibility,
  • Feel stronger and more grounded,
  • Reduce recovery time between workouts,
  • Reduce chronic inflammation, 
  • Slow the aging process,
  • Reduce scar tissue adhesions after injuries or surgeries (if any),
  • Straighten scoliotic curves in the spine (if any),
  • Strengthen hips, knees, feet and ankles,
  • Dramatically reduce chances of future athletic injuries. 


If this looks, sounds or feels like possible fit for you, please visit my website at  www.DonatelliWellness.com to fill out the questionnaire.  You will then get a FREE, 15-min Telephone Consultation to discuss how my custom-tailored Rolfing program can help you. 

To Your Future Health, Wealth and Performance!


James J Donatelli
